/**********************************************************************
 * File:    machStrc/actvn.doc
 * Purpose: Describe activation records and continuation records.
 * Author:  Karl Abrahamson
 **********************************************************************/

An ACTIVATION holds information necessary to resume a deferred
or suspended computation.  Global variable the_act holds
information about the currently executing computation.

A CONTINUATION holds partial information necessary to resume a
deferred or suspended computation, and is used for a frame in the
run-time stack.  It lacks its own stack, state
and control, since those are provided from outside when the 
continuation is returned to.  

Continuations and activations are referenced counted.  Some (those in use 
in controls, etc.) are managed using reference counts, and some (those
pointed to directly to by entities, such as those in lazy entities)
are managed by the garbage collector.

------------------------------------------------------------------------
The fields of an activation are as follows.  Those for continuations
are a subset of these.

kind		0 - This activation is an ordinary activation, and when
		    resumed, will start at its program_ctr location.
		1 - This activation is the beginning of a lazy evaluation,
		    and its program_ctr points to the byte that holds
		    the environment size index.  The actual code starts
		    after that.
		2 - This activation has been terminated by another thread.
		    When it starts, set failure = TERMINATE_EX.

actmark		Used when marking activations during garbage collection.

ref_cnt		The reference count.  Only relevant for ref-count managed
		activations.

in_atomic	number of atomic-constructs currently inside.

progress	Tells if this activation has made progress since its
		last repause.  1 indicates progress, 0 indicates no
		progress.

waiting_applies When a MULTI_APPLY_I or TAIL_MULTI_APPLY_I instruction
		is executed, it queues up REV_APPLY_I instructions, to
		be done when a RETURN_I instruction is done.
		waiting_applies tells how many REV_APPLY_I instuctions
		are queued up.

name		name of the currently executing function, for 
		reporting to user.

program_ctr	The address of the next instruction to execute.

type_binding_lists A list of binding lists for types.  When a type is 
		  fetched from an environment, variables in the type are 
		  subject to the bindings in first list in this list.
		  (If this list is NIL, then its first member is considered
		  to be NIL.)

stack		The current stack.  (The stack is used for holding
		temporary results and for parameter passing.)

state_a		This is the current state.

state_hold	A list of states that have been pushed by PRESERVE_I 
		instructions.  

control		The current control.  This holds activations that have
		been suspended as part of backtracking or concurrent
		execution (stream or mix).

embedding_tries The control can contain nodes that belong to Try 
		expressions.  It is possible for it to contain 
		nodes that belong to constructs that this thread has 
		already exited.

		embedding_tries is a stack of the identities of nodes in
		the control that correspond to constructs that the
		current thread is inside, with more recently entered
		constructs having their ids closer to the top (front).

embedding_marks This is similar to embedding_tries, but tells identities
		of MARK_F nodes that correspond to CutHere constructs that
		the current thread is inside.

env		The environment for this activation.

num_entries	Number of entries in env that are being used by this 
		activation.

exception_list	The head of this list is the current value of `exception'.
		Other members are for try-elses in which the current
		try-else is embedded.  If this list is NIL, then there
		is no currently active value of 'exception'.  In a 
		continuation, this field is called EXCEPTION_LIST.

continuation	This is the sub-activation to return to, when the current
		activation does a RETURN_I.  There are no stack, states
		or control fields.  

st_depth	The depth of the current run-time stack.  (That is, this
		is the length of the chain of continuations pointed to
		by continuation.)

coroutines	A list whose head is a list of coroutines that are
		waiting for execution, and whose tail is a list of 
		coroutines that have executed and paused.  If this field
		is NIL, then both of those lists are NIL.

trap_vec_a	The current trap vector.

trap_vec_hold	A list of trap vectors for traps or untraps in which 
		this computation is embedded.  These are the ones that
		will be brought back when the trap or untrap is exited.

result_type_instrs  Address of END_LET_I-terminated instructions that leave,
		    on the type stack, the type of the result that will be 
		    on stack at a RETURN_I instruction.

=========================================================================
Activations and continuations are also stored with functions and 
lazy entities.  Not all fields are used.  Used fields are as follows.

Function: (Continuation)
  ref_cnt
  program_ctr
  env
  num_entries
  result_type_instrs
  continuation  (Not a true continuation.  Used to link continuation cells
		 that are in function nodes into a chain for scanning
		 during the collect phase of garbage collection.)

Lazy: (Activation)
  ref_cnt
  exception
  program_ctr
  env
  num_entries
  states
  trap_vecs
  result_type_instrs

Lazy List: (Activation)
  All fields
  

Activations and continuations can occur in entities.  There, the entity
is sole owner of the activation or continuation.  When an activation or
continuation occurs outside an entity, it is managed by a reference
count.


